A debounce function is a higher-order function that limits the rate at which a given function is invoked by delaying its execution until a specified period has passed since the last invocation.

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timeoutId;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
      func.apply(this, args);
    }, delay);
  };
}

// Example usage:
const logMessage = () => console.log('Hello, world!'); // Original function
const debouncedLog = debounce(logMessage, 1000); // Create a debounced version with 1000ms delay

// Simulate calls (in a real scenario, this might be tied to an event like scrolling):
debouncedLog(); // This will execute logMessage after 1 second
debouncedLog(); // This resets the timer, so logMessage executes after another 1 second from this call
```
